{"title_page": "Nokia N90", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox Mobile phone\n| name = Nokia N90\n| image = Nokia N90 Camera flickr 178946625.jpg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| manufacturer = [[Nokia]]\n| carrier = \n| available = 2005\n| screen = [[Thin-film transistor|TFT]], 262,144 colours, 352\u00d7416 pixels\n| exterior_screen = TFT, 65,536 colours, 128\u00d7128 pixels\n| camera = 2 Megapixels\n| 2nd_camera = \n| operatingsystem = [[Symbian OS]] v8.1a, Series 60 Feature Pack 3\n| input = [[Keypad]]\n| cpu = TI OMAP 1710, 32-bit RISC ARM9 @ 220&nbsp;MHz\n| predecessor = Nokia 6260\n| successor = [[Nokia N93]]\n| ringtone = [[MP3]], 64 Channels Polyphonic\n| memory = 48 [[MegaByte|MB]]\n| memory_card = [[MultiMediaCard|DV RS-MMC / MMC-Mobile]]\n| networks = [[GPRS]], [[Enhanced Data Rates for GSM Evolution|EDGE]], [[WCDMA]]\n| connectivity = [[USB]] (v2.0), [[Bluetooth]] (v1.2)\n| battery = BL-5B, 3.7&nbsp;V, 760&nbsp;mAh\n| size = 112x51x24&nbsp;mm\n| form = Clamshell\n| weight = 173&nbsp;g\n| music = \n| related = [[Nokia N92]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Nokia N90''' is a [[smartphone]], announced as part of [[Nokia]]'s then-new line of multimedia devices, [[Nokia Nseries|Nseries]], on April 27, 2005.<ref>http://company.nokia.com/en/news/press-releases/2005/04/27/twist-and-shoot-nokia-n90-makes-its-premiere</ref> It had a unique [[swivel]] design encompassing four 'modes'. It has two displays and has a camera with [[Carl Zeiss]] optics and integrated [[Flash (photography)|flash]], and can record video with audio. The screen can be swiveled 270\u00b0 to let the phone be handled more like a conventional video camera. The [[swivel lens|camera lens]] can also be swiveled. The phone has no vibration feature. The 2.1-inch display has a pixel density of 259 ppi, which made it incredibly sharp and the crispest Nokia screen at the time, and continued to be joint-highest with the [[Nokia N80|N80]], [[Nokia E60|E60]] and [[Nokia E70|E70]] for four years, before being beaten by the [[Nokia N900]] in 2009 with 267 ppi. The Nokia N90 can print with some printers over USB or over Bluetooth.<ref>https://www.sellmyphone.org.uk/nokia/phone/nokia_n90</ref>\n\nIt uses the [[Nokia Series 60|Series 60]] 2nd Edition, Feature Pack 3 user interface on top of the [[Symbian OS]] 8.1a operating system. Later revisions also shipped with Version 2 of the [[Nokia Lifeblog]] software. The Nokia N90 began shipping in Q2 2005 in most markets, but didn't appear in the [[US]] until Q1 2006. It was succeeded by the [[Nokia N93]].\n\nThe N90 was usually bundled with a 64 MB or 128 MB DV-[[RS-MMC]] memory card and a USB data cable.\n\nComplaints about the N90 include high [[price]], large [[volume|size]] and [[mass|weight]] and \"chunkiness.\"\n\n== Specification sheet ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n| Form factor || Clamshell / Transformer\n|- \n| Operating System || [[Symbian OS]] v8.1a, Series 60 Feature Pack 3\n|-\n| Processor || TI OMAP 1710, 32-bit RISC ARM9 @ 220&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n| GSM frequencies || 900/1800/1900&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n| GPRS || Yes, class 10\n|-\n| EDGE (EGPRS) || Yes, class 10\n|-\n| WCDMA || Yes (2100&nbsp;MHz)\n|-\n| Main screen || TFT, 262,144 colours, 352\u00d7416 pixels (2.1&nbsp;inches diagonally)\n|-\n| Second screen || TFT, 65,536 colours, 128\u00d7128 pixels\n|-\n| Camera || 2.0 megapixels (photo light, 20\u00d7 digital zoom)\n|-\n| Video recording || Yes, CIF (max. clip length 2 h)\n|-\n| Multimedia Messaging || Yes\n|-\n| Video calls || Yes\n|-\n| Push to talk || Yes\n|-\n| Java support || Yes, MIDP 2.0\n|-\n| Built-in memory || 31 MB\n|-\n| Memory card slot || Yes, [[MultiMediaCard|DV RS-MMC / MMC-Mobile]]\n|-\n| Bluetooth || Yes\n|-\n| Infrared || No\n|-\n| Data cable support || Yes\n|-\n| Browser || WAP 2.0 XHTML / HTML\n|-\n| Email || Yes\n|-\n| Music player || Yes, stereo\n|-\n| Radio || No\n|-\n| Video Player || Yes\n|-\n| Polyphonic tones || Yes, 64 chords\n|-\n| Mp3 ringtones || Yes\n|-\n| HF speakerphone || Yes\n|-\n| Offline mode || Yes\n|-\n| Battery || BL-5B (760 mAh)\n|-\n| Talk time || 3 hours\n|-\n| Standby time || 12 days (288 hours)\n|-\n| Weight || 173&nbsp;grams\n|-\n| Dimensions || 112\u00d751\u00d724 millimeters\n|-\n| Availability || Q2/2005\n|-\n| Else || Quickoffice office suite\n|}\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[File:Nokia N90 Open flickr 178946286.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The N90 opened in a normal clamshell way]]\nThe N90 was featured in [[Tom Clancy's Splinter Cell: Double Agent]] as a [[billboard]].\n\nThe N90 was shown in an episode of NCIS.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Nokia products]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Nokia N90}}\n* [http://www.symbian-freak.com/news/1105/n90_n91_bestaward.htm Twice The Honor: Nokia N90 and Nokia N91 Win A \"Best Of What's New ...]\n* [http://www.symbian-freak.com/news/1105/n90_us_ready.htm Award-Winning Nokia N90 Now Shipping in the US]\n* [http://www.symbian-freak.com/news/0805/n90.htm Nokia N90 voted European Media Phone of the Year]\n* [http://www.nokia.com/N90 Official Nokia N90 Product Page]\n* [http://www.nseriestalk.com N Series Talk] Nokia N Series Forums and Community\n* [http://n90.bloggercomm.com/ Official N90 Blog]\n\n=== Reviews ===\n* [https://www.mobilesdetail.com/phone/nokia-n90-tnf Mobiles detail]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060316014941/http://www.infosyncworld.com/reviews/n/6108.html InfoSync World]\n* [http://www.mobile-review.com/review/nokia-n90-en.shtml Mobile Review]\n* [http://www.3g.co.uk/PR/Oct2005/2084.htm 3G.co.uk]\n* [http://www.mobileburn.com/review.jsp?Page=1&Id=1689 Mobile Burn]\n* [http://www.cooltechzone.com/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=1915&Itemid=0&limit=1&limitstart=0 Cooltech Zone]\n* [http://www.camera-phones-spot.com/nokia_camera_phones/nokia_n90/ Camera Phones Spot]\n* [http://www.mobique.com/nokia/n90/index.php Mobique]\n\n{{Nokia phones}}\n\n[[Category:Nokia mobile phones|N90]]\n[[Category:Smartphones]]\n\n\n[[de:Nokia Nseries#Nokia N90]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox Mobile phone\n| name = Nokia N90\n| image = Nokia N90 Camera flickr 178946625.jpg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| manufacturer = [[Nokia]]\n| carrier = \n| available = 2005\n| screen = [[Thin-film transistor|TFT]], 262,144 colours, 352\u00d7416 pixels\n| exterior_screen = TFT, 65,536 colours, 128\u00d7128 pixels\n| camera = 2 Megapixels\n| 2nd_camera = \n| operatingsystem = [[Symbian OS]] v8.1a, Series 60 Feature Pack 3\n| input = [[Keypad]]\n| cpu = TI OMAP 1710, 32-bit RISC ARM9 @ 220&nbsp;MHz\n| predecessor = Nokia 6260\n| successor = [[Nokia N93]]\n| ringtone = [[MP3]], 64 Channels Polyphonic\n| memory = 48 [[MegaByte|MB]]\n| memory_card = [[MultiMediaCard|DV RS-MMC / MMC-Mobile]]\n| networks = [[GPRS]], [[Enhanced Data Rates for GSM Evolution|EDGE]], [[WCDMA]]\n| connectivity = [[USB]] (v2.0), [[Bluetooth]] (v1.2)\n| battery = BL-5B, 3.7&nbsp;V, 760&nbsp;mAh\n| size = 112x51x24&nbsp;mm\n| form = Clamshell\n| weight = 173&nbsp;g\n| music = \n| related = [[Nokia N92]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Nokia N90''' is a [[smartphone]], announced as part of [[Nokia]]'s then-new line of multimedia devices, [[Nokia Nseries|Nseries]], on April 27, 2005.<ref>http://company.nokia.com/en/news/press-releases/2005/04/27/twist-and-shoot-nokia-n90-makes-its-premiere</ref> It had a unique [[swivel]] design encompassing four 'modes'. It has two displays and has a camera with [[Carl Zeiss]] optics and integrated [[Flash (photography)|flash]], and can record video with audio. The screen can be swiveled 270\u00b0 to let the phone be handled more like a conventional video camera. The [[swivel lens|camera lens]] can also be swiveled. The phone has no vibration feature. The 2.1-inch display has a pixel density of 259 ppi, which made it incredibly sharp and the crispest Nokia screen at the time, and continued to be joint-highest with the [[Nokia N80|N80]], [[Nokia E60|E60]] and [[Nokia E70|E70]] for four years, before being beaten by the [[Nokia N900]] in 2009 with 267 ppi. The Nokia N90 can print with some printers over USB or over Bluetooth.<ref>https://www.sellmyphone.org.uk/nokia/phone/nokia_n90</ref>\n\nIt uses the [[Nokia Series 60|Series 60]] 2nd Edition, Feature Pack 3 user interface on top of the [[Symbian OS]] 8.1a operating system. Later revisions also shipped with Version 2 of the [[Nokia Lifeblog]] software. The Nokia N90 began shipping in Q2 2005 in most markets, but didn't appear in the [[US]] until Q1 2006. It was succeeded by the [[Nokia N93]].\n\nThe N90 was usually bundled with a 64 MB or 128 MB DV-[[RS-MMC]] memory card and a USB data cable.\n\nComplaints about the N90 include high [[price]], large [[volume|size]] and [[mass|weight]] and \"chunkiness.\"\n\n== Specification sheet ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n| Form factor || Clamshell / Transformer\n|- \n| Operating System || [[Symbian OS]] v8.1a, Series 60 Feature Pack 3\n|-\n| Processor || TI OMAP 1710, 32-bit RISC ARM9 @ 220&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n| GSM frequencies || 900/1800/1900&nbsp;MHz\n|-\n| GPRS || Yes, class 10\n|-\n| EDGE (EGPRS) || Yes, class 10\n|-\n| WCDMA || Yes (2100&nbsp;MHz)\n|-\n| Main screen || TFT, 262,144 colours, 352\u00d7416 pixels (2.1&nbsp;inches diagonally)\n|-\n| Second screen || TFT, 65,536 colours, 128\u00d7128 pixels\n|-\n| Camera || 2.0 megapixels (photo light, 20\u00d7 digital zoom)\n|-\n| Video recording || Yes, CIF (max. clip length 2 h)\n|-\n| Multimedia Messaging || Yes\n|-\n| Video calls || Yes\n|-\n| Push to talk || Yes\n|-\n| Java support || Yes, MIDP 2.0\n|-\n| Built-in memory || 31 MB\n|-\n| Memory card slot || Yes, [[MultiMediaCard|DV RS-MMC / MMC-Mobile]]\n|-\n| Bluetooth || Yes\n|-\n| Infrared || No\n|-\n| Data cable support || Yes\n|-\n| Browser || WAP 2.0 XHTML / HTML\n|-\n| Email || Yes\n|-\n| Music player || Yes, stereo\n|-\n| Radio || No\n|-\n| Video Player || Yes\n|-\n| Polyphonic tones || Yes, 64 chords\n|-\n| Mp3 ringtones || Yes\n|-\n| HF speakerphone || Yes\n|-\n| Offline mode || Yes\n|-\n| Battery || BL-5B (760 mAh)\n|-\n| Talk time || 3 hours\n|-\n| Standby time || 12 days (288 hours)\n|-\n| Weight || 173&nbsp;grams\n|-\n| Dimensions || 112\u00d751\u00d724 millimeters\n|-\n| Availability || Q2/2005\n|-\n| Else || Quickoffice office suite\n|}\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[File:Nokia N90 Open flickr 178946286.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The N90 opened in a normal clamshell way]]\nThe N90 was featured in [[Tom Clancy's Splinter Cell: Double Agent]] as a [[billboard]].\n\nThe N90 was shown in an episode of NCIS.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Nokia products]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Nokia N90}}\n* [http://www.symbian-freak.com/news/1105/n90_n91_bestaward.htm Twice The Honor: Nokia N90 and Nokia N91 Win A \"Best Of What's New ...]\n* [http://www.symbian-freak.com/news/1105/n90_us_ready.htm Award-Winning Nokia N90 Now Shipping in the US]\n* [http://www.symbian-freak.com/news/0805/n90.htm Nokia N90 voted European Media Phone of the Year]\n* [http://www.nokia.com/N90 Official Nokia N90 Product Page]\n* [http://www.nseriestalk.com N Series Talk] Nokia N Series Forums and Community\n* [http://n90.bloggercomm.com/ Official N90 Blog]\n\n=== Reviews ===\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060316014941/http://www.infosyncworld.com/reviews/n/6108.html InfoSync World]\n* [http://www.mobile-review.com/review/nokia-n90-en.shtml Mobile Review]\n* [http://www.3g.co.uk/PR/Oct2005/2084.htm 3G.co.uk]\n* [http://www.mobileburn.com/review.jsp?Page=1&Id=1689 Mobile Burn]\n* [http://www.cooltechzone.com/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=1915&Itemid=0&limit=1&limitstart=0 Cooltech Zone]\n* [http://www.camera-phones-spot.com/nokia_camera_phones/nokia_n90/ Camera Phones Spot]\n* [http://www.mobique.com/nokia/n90/index.php Mobique]\n\n{{Nokia phones}}\n\n[[Category:Nokia mobile phones|N90]]\n[[Category:Smartphones]]\n\n\n[[de:Nokia Nseries#Nokia N90]]\n", "name_user": "Dhimanak", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eReviews)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nokia_N90"}
{"title_page": "Freydal", "text_new": "{{short description|16th century uncompleted illustrated prose work}}\n{{Italic title}}\n[[File:Freydal fol133.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|right|A scene from the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]]\u2019s ''Freydal'' Illuminated manuscript: Freydal jousts with Veit von Wolkenstein (fol.133)<ref>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|pp=177\u2013178}}</ref>]]\n'''''Freydal''''' is an uncompleted illustrated prose narrative commissioned by the [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Holy Roman Emperor, Maximilian I]] in the early 16th century. It was intended to be a romantic allegorical account of Maximilian's own participation in a series of [[Tournament (medieval)|jousting tournaments]] in the guise of the tale's eponymous hero, Freydal. In the story, Freydal takes part in the tournaments to prove that he is worthy to marry a princess, who is a fictionalised representation of Maximilian's late wife, [[Mary of Burgundy]].\n\nThe text was never completed, although a manuscript draft is held by the [[Austrian National Library]]. 256 [[Miniature (illuminated manuscript)|miniature paintings]] to accompany the text were created by court painters, and 255 are preserved in an [[illuminated manuscript]] \u2018tournament book\u2019 held by the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] in [[Vienna]]. These miniatures vividly record the different types of jousts that were popular at the time as well as the [[Masquerade ball|court masquerades]], or \u2018mummeries\u2019, that took place at the end of the day after each tournament. It is the most extensive visual record of late medieval tournaments and court masquerades that exists.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Albrecht D\u00fcrer - Portrait of Maximilian I - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|left|Portrait of [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian I]] by [[Albrecht D\u00fcrer]], 1519.]]\n[[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian I]] and his father [[Frederick III, Holy Roman Emperor|Frederick III]] were part of what was to become a long line of [[Holy Roman Emperors]] from the [[House of Habsburg]]. Maximilian was elected [[King of the Romans]] in 1486; upon his father's death in 1493 he succeeded to the throne of the Holy Roman Empire.<ref>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|p=303}}</ref>\n\nDuring his reign, Maximilian commissioned a number of [[Renaissance humanism|humanist]] scholars and artists to assist him in completing a series of projects, in different art forms, intended to immortalize his life and deeds and those of his Habsburg ancestors.<ref name=\"Watanabe-O'Kelly94\">{{harvnb| Watanabe-O'Kelly|2000|p=94}}</ref> He referred to these projects as ''Gedechtnus'' (\"memorial\"),<ref name=\"Kleinschmidt162\">{{harvnb|Kleinschmidt|2008|p=162}}</ref> and included a series of stylised autobiographical works: ''Freydal'', the prose romance ''[[Weisskunig]]'', and the poem ''[[Theuerdank]]''.<ref name=\"Watanabe-O'Kelly94\"/>\n\n''Freydal'' and ''Theuerdank'' are closely linked and together give an allegorical account of the events leading to Maximilian's marriage to [[Mary of Burgundy]] in 1477.<ref name=moma120>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|p=120}}</ref> Mary died five years later, in 1482.<ref>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|p=300}}</ref> In ''Freydal'', which is partly a tribute to Mary,<ref name=\"Clephan 1995 88\">{{harvnb|Clephan|1995|p=88}}</ref> the eponymous hero pursues his fair lady by [[jousting]] in [[Tournament (medieval)|tournaments]].<ref name=Freeman>{{harvnb|Freeman|2019}}</ref> ''Theuerdank'' is effectively a sequel in which the hero overcomes dangers on the journey to his wedding.<ref name=moma120/> ''Freydal'' has a comedic tone which contrasts with ''Theuerdank'', which has more of the character of a tragedy.<ref name=McLaren/>\n\nThe theme of ''Freydal'' reflects Maximilian's lifelong enthusiasm for jousting. He attended his first tournament at the age of 14 and was captivated by its traditions and spectacle.<ref name=Freeman/> He staged many tournaments, including those to celebrate his wedding to Mary of Burgundy in 1477, his coronation as King of the Romans in 1486 and on the occasion of the [[First Congress of Vienna]] in 1515.<ref name=Freeman/> Maximilian was himself a participant in tournaments from 1485 until 1511, when he was in his 50s.<ref>{{harvnb|Anderson|2017|pp=104\u2013105}}</ref> His affinity for jousting contributed to his [[soubriquet]] the \u201clast knight\u201d.<ref name=Freeman/>\n[[File:Freydal fol164.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|right|Post-tournament festivities: grotesque-style dancers or mummers dance a [[moresca]] while Freydal, in a mask and holding torches, looks on (''Freydal'' ms. fol.164, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum|KMW]])<ref name=Locke123/>]]\n\n==Creation and history==\nMaximilian appears to have begun planning in 1502.<ref name=moma123>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|p=123}}</ref> The name ''Freydal'' was derived from ''Freyd-alb'', meaning \"white joyful young man\"<ref>{{harvnb|Strobl|1913|p=4}}</ref> In that year, he instructed his court taylor, Martin Trummer \"to have drawn in a book all those costumes as yet seen in mummeries organised by his majesty\".<ref name=moma123/> A \u201cmummery\u201d was a late medieval courtly [[Masquerade ball|masquerade]] or costumed dance.<ref name=moma122>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|p=122}}</ref>\n\nThis developed into the commissioning of planning sketches for the entire work, created over the next ten years.<ref name=moma123/> They were drawn in pen on [[laid paper]], using brown and black ink with watercolour over black chalk and leadpoint.<ref name=moma123/> A collection of 203 of these are housed in the [[National Gallery of Art]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|pp=120, 123}}</ref> A small number of additional drawings are held at the [[British Museum]] and the [[Vatican Library]].<ref name=moma123/>\n\nMaximilian took a leading part in the creation of the work.<ref name=Clephan87>{{harvnb|Clephan|1995|p=87}}</ref> His instructions on the subjects to be illustrated as well as corrections, in his own hand, of some of the proofs have survived. In 1511, Maximilian dictated some of the text to his secretary, Max Trytssaurwein,<ref name=Clephan87/> (or Marx Treitzsauerwein<ref>{{harvnb|Kleinschmidt|2008|p=178}}</ref>) and the following year wrote \"''Freydal'' is half conceived, the largest part of which we have made in Cologne\".<ref name=moma123/> The work was never completed,<ref name=Locke121>{{harvnb|Locke|2015|p=121}}</ref> however, and the text exists only in draft form.<ref name=moma121>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|p=121}}</ref> The manuscript text dictated to Treitzsauerwein, and corrected in Maximilian's hand, is held by the [[Austrian National Library]] in [[Vienna]].<ref>{{harvnb|Silver|2002|p=63}}</ref>\n[[File:German 16th Century, Freydal, The Book of Jousts and Tournament of Emperor Maximilian I - Combats on Horseback (Jousts)(Volume II), c. 1515, NGA 216067.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Planning sketch for ''Freydal'', National Gallery of Art, Washington]]\n\nAlthough the text was never finalised, 256 high quality [[Miniature (illuminated manuscript)|miniatures]]<ref name=moma121/> were created between 1512 and 1515 to illustrate the text.<ref name=moma120/> These were painted on paper in [[gouache]] with gold and silver highlights over pen, pencil and leadpoint<ref name=moma120/> by two dozen anonymous<ref name=McLaren>{{harvnb|McLaren|2019}}</ref> court artists under the direction of the imperial master-taylor.<ref name=Locke121/> All but one of the paintings are preserved in an [[illuminated manuscript]] \u2018tournament book\u2019 held by the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] in Vienna.<ref name=moma120/> The remaining painting has been missing since at least 1600.<ref name=moma121/>\n\nIt was intended to print and publish the work with [[woodcut]] illustrations derived from the miniatures.<ref name=Locke121/> Although Maximilian never succeeded in doing this,<ref name=Locke121/> and the text remained only a draft, five of the illustrations were trial printed.<ref name=moma121/> These were from woodcuts made in about 1516 by [[Albrecht D\u00fcrer]], albeit the cutting was somewhat rough. A sixth woodcut has been attributed to [[Lucas Cranach the Elder]].<ref name=Kurth36>{{harvnb|Kurth|1963|p=36}}</ref> One of the woodcut blocks has survived, and is held by the [[Kupferstichkabinett Berlin]].<ref>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|p=129}}</ref>\n\nIn modern times, the Kunsthistorisches Museum illuminated manuscript tournament book has been published twice. A multi-volume edition, edited by [[Quirin von Leitner]] ([[:de:Quirin von Leitner|de]]), was published in Vienna in stages between 1880 and 1882.<ref name=Clephan87/><ref>{{harvnb|von Leitner|1880\u20131882}}</ref> In 2019, the German publisher, [[Taschen]], published the entire tournament book in a single volume, edited by Stefan Krause.<ref name=McLaren/><ref>{{harvnb|Krause|2019}}</ref>\n\n==Content==\n\n===Narrative===\nBased on the draft text preserved in the Austrian National Library,<ref>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|pp=121, 122 note 2}}; {{harvnb|Silver|2002|pp=63\u201364}}</ref> the story is an account of a series of [[Tournament (medieval)|tournaments]] in which Freydal&nbsp;\u2013 a young knight and Maximilian's literary ''[[alter ego]]''&nbsp;\u2013 demonstrates his valour in combat in order to earn honour and fame<ref name=Silver64>{{harvnb|Silver|2002|p=64}}</ref> and to win the hand of a princess.<ref name=moma121/> Freydal is the son of a \u201cmighty prince\u201d and he is born with \u201cnoble virtue\u201d; his heraldic colours are white, red, and black, symbolising purity, fire, and bravery.<ref name=Silver64/>\n\n[[File:Freydal 01.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|right|Freydal in a \u201cjoust of war\u201d (''Antzogen-Rennen'') with Wolfgang von F\u00fcrstenberg (''Freydal'' ms. fol.17, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum|KMW]])<ref>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|pp=172,174}}</ref>]]\nThe narrative begins with three noble ladies asking Freydal to compete in the tournaments.<ref name=moma121/> A description of sixty-four tournaments follows in a ritualised and repetitive pattern.<ref name=Silver64/> Each is hosted by one of the finest courts in the land and comprises two different types of jousting; a foot combat; and a masquerade ball.<ref name=moma121/> Freydal competes in each tournament and almost always wins.<ref name=Clephan87/> Once all the tournaments are completed, Freydal receives a letter from one of the noble ladies who, it transpires, is a powerful queen; in the letter, she professes her love for him. The narrative ends with Freydal setting out to search for her, and ''Theuerdank'' then takes up the subsequent story.<ref name=moma121/>\n\nThe work reflects Maximilian's vanity, as exemplified by a poem which forms part of the draft text:<ref name=\"Clephan 1995 88\"/>{{Quotation|This did the gallant Freydal<br>In knightly deeds of fame<br>Thus rendering illustrious<br>The glories of his name.<br>His virtues and his goodness<br>Are manifest to all;<br>His many glorious triumphs<br>At tilt, at masks and ball...<br>His like will ne\u2019er be seen again.<ref>translation {{harvnb|Clephan|1995|p=88, note 1}}</ref>}}\n\nHowever, the tournaments described are based on encounters Maximilian actually had. This is evidenced by a list of people involved in the story in the first seven [[Paper quire|quire]]s of the draft text, and who are known to have been actual courtiers.<ref name=Silver64/>\n\n===Illuminated manuscript tournament book===\n[[File:Freydal 02.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|left|Freydal in a \u201cjoust of war with flying and exploding shields\u201d (''Geschifttartschen-Rennen'') with Sigmund von Welsperg (''Freydal'' ms. fol. 29, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum|KMW]])<ref>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|pp=175\u2013176}}</ref>]]\nThe miniatures in the tournament book manuscript illustrate the types of [[jousting]] popular at the time, both on horse and on foot.<ref name=McLaren/> Freydal features in each illustrated combat and his opponent is an historical figure with whom Maximilian actually jousted.<ref name=McLaren/> Each picture, in the lower margin, identifies the name of the opponent and the other courtiers depicted.<ref name=Locke123>{{harvnb|Locke|2015|p=123}}</ref> Other tournament books exist, but ''Freydal'' is the largest from the late Middle Ages<ref name=moma120/> and is considered the best executed; it is also the only one to show spectacular falls.<ref name=McLaren/>\n\nTwo types of joust, ''Rennen'' (or \u201cjousts of war\u201d where the lance has a sharpened tip<ref name= joust>{{harvnb|Jeep|2001|p=759}}; {{harvnb|Silver|2002|p=63}}</ref>) and ''Stechen'' (or \u201cjousts of peace\u201d where the lance has a blunted tip<ref name= joust/>) are depicted for each tournament.<ref name=Clephan87/><ref name=moma121/> Within these two broad groupings, eleven sub-types are shown.<ref name=moma121/> In the ''Welsches Gestecht'' (Italian joust of peace) a board separates the jousters so that they can ride more closely to each other and strike their opponent frontally with greater force. This results in a spectacular splintering of the lances. In the ''Scharfrennen'' (joust of war with flying shields) the shield is shown loosely fixed to the rider's breastplate, the aim being to dislodge it. In contrast, the objective of the ''Antzogenrennen'' is to unseat the opponent and his shield is fixed to his armour.<ref name=moma121/> The ''Feldrennen'' (or ''Kampfrennen'') jousts replicate skirmishes in war and the riders wear battlefield armour. The rarest type of joust depicted is the ''Kr\u00f6nlrennen'' where one rider wears the armour of a joust of peace but wields the lance of a joust of war and the other rider  has the opposite combination.<ref name=moma122/>\n\nOne of the most spectacular jousts depicted is the ''Bundrennen'' (joust of war with flying shields without [[bevors]])<ref name=moma121/> and its variation, ''Geschifttartschen-Rennen'' (joust of war with flying and exploding shields).<ref name=moma125>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|p=125}}</ref> In the ''Bundrennen'', the shield is held in place on the rider's breastplate with a complicated spring mechanism and when it is struck in the right place by the opponent it is ejected high into the air.<ref name=moma121/> The ''Geschifttartschen-Rennen'' increases the spectacle by attaching multiple triangular platelets to the shield which, when the shield is ejected, come loose and explode into the air like a firework display.<ref name=moma125/> Maximilian claimed to have invented this type of joust.<ref name=Freeman/> \n[[File:Freydal 05.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|right|Foot combat between Freydal and Claude de Vaudry (''Freydal'' ms. fol. 39, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum|KMW]])<ref name=moma120/>]]\nIn each of the tournaments, the participants are shown engaging in a foot combat. A variety of weapons are used, including [[Mace (bludgeon)|iron clubs]] (''Eisenkolben''), [[Flail (weapon)|flails]] (''Drischel''), swords (''Turnierschwert'')<ref name=krause179>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|p=179}}</ref> and daggers.<ref name=krause181>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|p=181}}</ref> The ''[[Melee (tournament)|m\u00eal\u00e9e]]'' is also shown in the manuscript.<ref name=Clephan87/>\n\nAfter each of the sixty-four tournaments is a scene depicting a [[moresca]] (a pantomime dance) or other post-tournament festivities with male courtiers, including the knights who had competed in the tournament, dressing up to dance in a variety of exotic costumes.<ref name=Locke121/> Known as \u2018mummeries\u2019, these were a regular feature of the evening entertainment after tournaments.<ref name=moma122/>\n\nThe male courtiers in the mummeries in the manuscript dress up, amongst other things, in costumes based on nationality or ethnicity, for example [[Ottoman Turks|Turkish]], [[Republic of Venice|Venetian]] or [[Burgundian Netherlands|Burgundian]] costume, or as animals such as [[apes]] and creatures with bird's heads.<ref name=Locke121/> In one masquerade illustrated, the male participants engage in [[cross-dressing]] and wear women's gowns.<ref name=moma122/>\n\nIn each scene, all the men are dressed in the same costume and normally wear a mask. Women, however, are always shown wearing their usual court attire.<ref name=Locke121/> In each of these post-tournament pictures, Freydal appears carrying a torch and wearing a mask.<ref name=Locke121/> The ''Freydal'' illustrations constitute the most extensive pictorial record of these late medieval court masquerades.<ref name=moma122/>\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = center\n | header = <br>Scenes from the Kunsthistorisches Museum ''Freydal'' illuminated manuscript\n | total_width = 725\n | image_style = border:none;\n | perrow = 3\n\n | image2 = Freydal KK5073.jpg\n | alt2 = Flying shields\n | caption2 = ''Scharfrennen''&nbsp;\u2013 joust of war with flying shields (fol.157)\n\n | image1 = Stechen gegen Graf Sigmund von Hardegk.jpg\n | alt1 = Stechen\n | caption1 = ''Stechen''&nbsp;\u2013 joust of peace, against Sigmund von Hardegk (fol.106)\n\n | image3 = Freydal fol14.jpg\n | alt3 = Italian\n | caption3 = ''Welsches Gestecht''&nbsp;\u2013 Italian joust of peace (fol.14)\n\n | image4 = Freydal fol156 Mummerei.jpg\n | alt4 = Mummery\n | caption4 = Mummery festivities (fol.156)\n\n | image6 = Masquerade, Freydal manuscript, folio 207.jpg\n | alt6 = Cross-dressing mummery \n | caption6 = Cross-dressing mummery (fol. 207)\n\n | image5 = Freydal fol083.jpg\n | alt5 = Flail\n | caption5 = Foot combat with flails against Wilhelm Auer von Herrenkirchen zu Neudorf (fol.83)<ref name=krause179/>\n\n}}\n==Significance==\nTournament books were a feature of late medieval and renaissance courtly culture and provide a graphic record of the jousting and it\u2019s rituals. Notable examples include [[Le Livre des tournois|''King Ren\u00e9's Tournament Book'']] and the tournament books of the [[Electors of Saxony]].<ref name=KrauseNGA>{{harvnb|Krause|2014\u20132015}}</ref> However, the ''Freydal'' illuminated manuscript is considered the most important<ref name=KrauseNGA/> and precious<ref name=Clephan87/> of this genre.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin|60em}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://etheses.whiterose.ac.uk/18205/ |title= The Tournament and its Role in the Court Culture of Emperor Maximilian I (1459-1519) |first=Natalie|last=Anderson |date=2017 |publisher=University of Leeds White Rose eTheses|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Robert Coltman|last= Clephan|title=The Mediaeval Tournament|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=aLzW7-TaSmYC&printsec=frontcover&dq=inauthor:%22Robert+Coltman+Clephan%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjCiaPqpermAhWpSRUIHee3DRsQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=1995|orig-year=1919|publisher=Courier Corporation|isbn=978-0-486-28620-4|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite news |first=Laura|last=Freeman|title= The joy of jousting |url= https://www.spectator.co.uk/2019/05/the-joy-of-jousting/ |newspaper=The Spectator |date= 4 May 2019 |accessdate=9 January 2020|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=John M. |last=Jeep|title=Medieval Germany: An Encyclopedia|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=PzorDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=isbn:9781351665407&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwim1pnu3fbmAhWQY8AKHcxYB6cQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=2001|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-351-66540-7|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Harald|last= Kleinschmidt|title=Ruling the Waves: Emperor Maximilian I, the Search for Islands and the Transformation of the European World Picture C. 1500|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vWEiAQAAIAAJ|date=2008|publisher=Antiquariaat Forum|isbn=978-90-6194-020-3|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite web |url= https://www.nga.gov/research/casva/research-projects/research-reports-archive/krause-2014-2015.html |title= Freydal, the Tournament Book of Emperor Maximilian I: The Washington Manuscript|first=Stefan |last= Krause |date=2014\u20132015|publisher=National Gallery of Art, Washington D.C.|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Stefan|last=Krause|editor-first=Sabine|display-editors=etal |editor-last=Haag|chapter= Die ritterspiel als ritter Freydalb hat gethon aus ritterlichem gmute \u2013 Das Turnierbuch Freydal Kaiser Maximilians I. |chapter-url= https://www.academia.edu/14910953/Das_Turnierbuch_Freydal_Kaiser_Maximilians_I |title=Kaiser Maximilian I: der letzte Ritter und das h\u00f6fische Turnier|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aSaRngEACAAJ|year=2014|publisher=Schnell & Steiner|isbn=978-3-7954-2842-6|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-first=Stefan |editor-last=Krause|title=Das Turnierbuch Kaiser Maximilians I.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=umw1vwEACAAJ|year=2019|publisher=Taschen|isbn=978-3-8365-7681-9|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Willi|last=Kurth|title=The Complete Woodcuts of Albrecht D\u00fcrer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U-RXmsclHiAC&pg=PA36|date=1963|publisher=Courier Corporation|isbn=978-0-486-21097-1|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Ralph P. |last=Locke|title=Music and the Exotic from the Renaissance to Mozart|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Dk8QCAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |date= 2015|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-01237-0|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite news |title= Freydal: the 16th-century comic that captures the thrill of jousting |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/books/what-to-read/freydal-16th-century-comic-captures-thrill-jousting/ |newspaper= [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date= 25 May 2019 |accessdate=4 January 2020|first= Iona|last=McLaren|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Larry|last=Silver|editor-first=Pia F.|editor-last= Cuneo|title=Artful Armies, Beautiful Battles: Art and Warfare in the Early Modern Europe|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7jBT4V3gtkwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=isbn:9004115889&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiytYnq4fbmAhXUSsAKHYf_B_UQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |year=2002|chapter=Shining Armor: Emperor Maximilian, Chivalry and War|publisher=Brill|isbn=90-04-11588-9|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Joseph|last= Strobl|title=Studien \u00fcber die literarische T\u00e4tigkeit Kaiser Maximilian I.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z5tsDwAAQBAJ|date=1913|publisher=Georg Reimer|isbn=978-3-11-148391-7|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite web |url= https://www.taschen.com/pages/en/catalogue/art/all/01184/facts.freydal_medieval_games_the_book_of_tournaments_of_emperor_maximilian_i.htm?ranMID=42784&ranEAID=hL3Qp0zRBOc&ranSiteID=hL3Qp0zRBOc-HKnVIgchCxGIascx0cyR6w |title= The Legendary Tales of Emperor Maximilian I|author=Taschen Catalogue |publisher=[[Taschen]]|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Terjanian|editor-first=Pierre|title=The Last Knight: The Art, Armor, and Ambition of Maximilian I|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=X-anDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=isbn:9781588396747&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi7kubikevmAhWMgVwKHeOrBtQQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=2019|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|isbn=978-1-58839-674-7|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= Freydal. Des Kaisers Maximilian I. Turniere und Mummereien |editor-last= von Leitner|editor-first=Quirin |year=1880\u20131882|url= https://archive.org/details/gri_33125010764674/page/n1 |publisher= Holzhausen|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Helen|last= Watanabe-O'Kelly|title=The Cambridge History of German Literature|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=feweVgIYXM8C&printsec=frontcover&dq=isbn:9780521785730&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiXkZnytermAhVTolwKHTMiB8wQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=2000|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-78573-0|ref= harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.org/details/gri_33125010764674/page/n1 ''Freydal. Des Kaisers Maximilian I. Turniere und Mummereien''] 1880-1882 edition (Q.von Leitner, ed.) from [[Internet Archive]]\n*[https://www.khm.at/en/learn/research/forschungsprojekte/kunsthistorische-projekte/freydal-das-turnierbuch-kaiser-maximilians-i-von-151215/ Kunsthistorisches Museum: ''Freydal'' \u2013 Das Turnierbuch Kaiser Maximilians I.] (in German)\n*[https://www.nga.gov/global-site-search-page.html?searchterm=Freydal National Gallery of Art, Washington D.C.: ''Freydal'' drawings]\n*[https://www.taschen.com/pages/en/catalogue/art/all/01184/facts.freydal_medieval_games_the_book_of_tournaments_of_emperor_maximilian_i.htm?ranMID=42784&ranEAID=hL3Qp0zRBOc&ranSiteID=hL3Qp0zRBOc-HKnVIgchCxGIascx0cyR6w Freydal. Medieval Games. The Book of Tournaments of Emperor Maximilian I], [[Taschen]] Catalogue (in English)\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Literature of the German Renaissance]]\n[[Category:16th-century books]]\n[[Category:16th-century illuminated manuscripts]]\n[[Category:Medieval tournament]]\n[[Category:Miniature painting]]\n[[Category:Paintings of the Kunsthistorisches Museum]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|16th century uncompleted illustrated prose work}}\n{{Italic title}}\n[[File:Freydal fol133.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|right|A scene from the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]]\u2019s ''Freydal'' Illuminated manuscript: Freydal jousts with Veit von Wolkenstein (fol.133)<ref>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|pp=177\u2013178}}</ref>]]\n'''''Freydal''''' is an uncompleted illustrated prose narrative commissioned by the [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Holy Roman Emperor, Maximilian I]] in the early 16th century. It was intended to be a romantic allegorical account of Maximilian's own participation in a series of [[Tournament (medieval)|jousting tournaments]] in the guise of the tale's eponymous hero, Freydal. In the story, Freydal takes part in the tournaments to prove that he is worthy to marry a princess, who is a fictionalised representation of Maximilian's late wife, [[Mary of Burgundy]].\n\nThe text was never completed, although a manuscript draft is held by the [[Austrian National Library]]. 256 [[Miniature (illuminated manuscript)|miniature paintings]] to accompany the text were created by court painters, and 255 are preserved in an [[illuminated manuscript]] \u2018tournament book\u2019 held by the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] in [[Vienna]]. These miniatures vividly record the different types of jousts that were popular at the time as well as the [[Masquerade ball|court masquerades]], or \u2018mummeries\u2019, that took place at the end of the day after each tournament. It is the most extensive visual record of late medieval tournaments and court masquerades that exists.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Albrecht D\u00fcrer - Portrait of Maximilian I - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|left|Portrait of [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian I]] by [[Albrecht D\u00fcrer]], 1519.]]\n[[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian I]] and his father [[Frederick III, Holy Roman Emperor|Frederick III]] were part of what was to become a long line of [[Holy Roman Emperors]] from the [[House of Habsburg]]. Maximilian was elected [[King of the Romans]] in 1486; upon his father's death in 1493 he succeeded to the throne of the Holy Roman Empire.<ref>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|p=303}}</ref>\n\nDuring his reign, Maximilian commissioned a number of [[Renaissance humanism|humanist]] scholars and artists to assist him in completing a series of projects, in different art forms, intended to immortalize his life and deeds and those of his Habsburg ancestors.<ref name=\"Watanabe-O'Kelly94\">{{harvnb| Watanabe-O'Kelly|2000|p=94}}</ref> He referred to these projects as ''Gedechtnus'' (\"memorial\"),<ref name=\"Kleinschmidt162\">{{harvnb|Kleinschmidt|2008|p=162}}</ref> and included a series of stylised autobiographical works: ''Freydal'', the prose romance ''[[Weisskunig]]'', and the poem ''[[Theuerdank]]''.<ref name=\"Watanabe-O'Kelly94\"/>\n\n''Freydal'' and ''Theuerdank'' are closely linked and together give an allegorical account of the events leading to Maximilian's marriage to [[Mary of Burgundy]] in 1477.<ref name=moma120>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|p=120}}</ref> Mary died five years later, in 1482.<ref>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|p=300}}</ref> In ''Freydal'', which is partly a tribute to Mary,<ref name=\"Clephan 1995 88\">{{harvnb|Clephan|1995|p=88}}</ref> the eponymous hero pursues his fair lady by [[jousting]] in [[Tournament (medieval)|tournaments]].<ref name=Freeman>{{harvnb|Freeman|2019}}</ref> ''Theuerdank'' is effectively a sequel in which the hero overcomes dangers on the journey to his wedding.<ref name=moma120/> ''Freydal'' has a comedic tone which contrasts with ''Theuerdank'', which has more of the character of a tragedy.<ref name=McLaren/>\n\nThe theme of ''Freydal'' reflects Maximilian's lifelong enthusiasm for jousting. He attended his first tournament at the age of 14 and was captivated by its traditions and spectacle.<ref name=Freeman/> He staged many tournaments, including those to celebrate his wedding to Mary of Burgundy in 1477, his coronation as King of the Romans in 1486 and on the occasion of the [[First Congress of Vienna]] in 1515.<ref name=Freeman/> Maximilian was himself a participant in tournaments from 1485 until 1511, when he was in his 50s.<ref>{{harvnb|Anderson|2017|pp=104\u2013105}}</ref> His affinity for jousting contributed to his [[soubriquet]] the \u201clast knight\u201d.<ref name=Freeman/>\n[[File:Freydal fol164.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|right|Post-tournament festivities: grotesque-style dancers or mummers dance a [[moresca]] while Freydal, in a mask and holding torches, looks on (''Freydal'' ms. fol.164, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum|KMW]])<ref name=Locke123/>]]\n\n==Creation and history==\nMaximilian appears to have begun planning in 1502.<ref name=moma123>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|p=123}}</ref> The name ''Freydal'' was derived from ''Freyd-alb'', meaning \"white joyful young man\"<ref>{{harvnb|Strobl|1913|p=4}}</ref> In that year, he instructed his court taylor, Martin Trummer \"to have drawn in a book all those costumes as yet seen in mummeries organised by his majesty\".<ref name=moma123/> A \u201cmummery\u201d was a late medieval courtly [[Masquerade ball|masquerade]] or costumed dance.<ref name=moma122>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|p=122}}</ref>\n\nThis developed into the commissioning of planning sketches for the entire work, created over the next ten years.<ref name=moma123/> They were drawn in pen on [[laid paper]], using brown and black ink with watercolour over black chalk and leadpoint.<ref name=moma123/> A collection of 203 of these are housed in the [[National Gallery of Art]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|pp=120, 123}}</ref> A small number of additional drawings are held at the [[British Museum]] and the [[Vatican Library]].<ref name=moma123/>\n\nMaximilian took a leading part in the creation of the work.<ref name=Clephan87>{{harvnb|Clephan|1995|p=87}}</ref> His instructions on the subjects to be illustrated as well as corrections, in his own hand, of some of the proofs have survived. In 1511, Maximilian dictated some of the text to his secretary, Max Trytssaurwein,<ref name=Clephan87/> (or Marx Treitzsauerwein<ref>{{harvnb|Kleinschmidt|2008|p=178}}</ref>) and the following year wrote \"''Freydal'' is half conceived, the largest part of which we have made in Cologne\".<ref name=moma123/> The work was never completed,<ref name=Locke121>{{harvnb|Locke|2015|p=121}}</ref> however, and the text exists only in draft form.<ref name=moma121>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|p=121}}</ref> The manuscript text dictated to Treitzsauerwein, and corrected in Maximilian's hand, is held by the [[Austrian National Library]] in [[Vienna]].<ref>{{harvnb|Silver|2002|p=63}}</ref>\n[[File:German 16th Century, Freydal, The Book of Jousts and Tournament of Emperor Maximilian I - Combats on Horseback (Jousts)(Volume II), c. 1515, NGA 216067.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Planning sketch for ''Freydal'', National Gallery of Art, Washington]]\n\nAlthough the text was never finalised, 256 high quality [[Miniature (illuminated manuscript)|miniatures]]<ref name=moma121/> were created between 1512 and 1515 to illustrate the text.<ref name=moma120/> These were painted on paper in [[gouache]] with gold and silver highlights over pen, pencil and leadpoint<ref name=moma120/> by two dozen anonymous<ref name=McLaren>{{harvnb|McLaren|2019}}</ref> court artists under the direction of the imperial master-taylor.<ref name=Locke121/> All but one of the paintings are preserved in an [[illuminated manuscript]] \u2018tournament book\u2019 held by the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] in Vienna.<ref name=moma120/> The remaining painting has been missing since at least 1600.<ref name=moma121/>\n\nIt was intended to print and publish the work with [[woodcut]] illustrations derived from the miniatures.<ref name=Locke121/> Although Maximilian never succeeded in doing this,<ref name=Locke121/> and the text remained only a draft, five of the illustrations were trial printed.<ref name=moma121/> These were from woodcuts made in about 1516 by [[Albrecht D\u00fcrer]], albeit the cutting was somewhat rough. A sixth woodcut has been attributed to [[Lucas Cranach the Elder]].<ref name=Kurth36>{{harvnb|Kurth|1963|p=36}}</ref> One of the woodcut blocks has survived, and is held by the [[Kupferstichkabinett Berlin]].<ref>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|p=129}}</ref>\n\nIn modern times, the Kunsthistorisches Museum illuminated manuscript tournament book has been published twice. A multi-volume edition, edited by [[Quirin von Leitner]] ([[:de:Quirin von Leitner|de]]), was published in Vienna in stages between 1880 and 1882.<ref name=Clephan87/><ref>{{harvnb|von Leitner|1880\u20131882}}</ref> In 2019, the German publisher, [[Taschen]], published the entire tournament book in a single volume, edited by Stefan Krause.<ref name=McLaren/><ref>{{harvnb|Krause|2019}}</ref>\n\n==Content==\n\n===Narrative===\nBased on the draft text preserved in the Austrian National Library,<ref>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|pp=121, 122 note 2}}; {{harvnb|Silver|2002|pp=63\u201364}}</ref> the story is an account of a series of [[Tournament (medieval)|tournaments]] in which Freydal&nbsp;\u2013 a young knight and Maximilian's literary ''[[alter ego]]''&nbsp;\u2013 demonstrates his valour in combat in order to earn honour and fame<ref name=Silver64>{{harvnb|Silver|2002|p=64}}</ref> and to win the hand of a princess.<ref name=moma121/> Freydal is the son of a \u201cmighty prince\u201d and he is born with \u201cnoble virtue\u201d; his heraldic colours are white, red, and black, symbolising purity, fire, and bravery.<ref name=Silver64/>\n\n[[File:Freydal 01.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|right|Freydal in a \u201cjoust of war\u201d (''Antzogen-Rennen'') with Wolfgang von F\u00fcrstenberg (''Freydal'' ms. fol.17, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum|KMW]])<ref>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|pp=172,174}}</ref>]]\nThe narrative begins with three noble ladies asking Freydal to compete in the tournaments.<ref name=moma121/> A description of sixty-four tournaments follows in a ritualised and repetitive pattern.<ref name=Silver64/> Each is hosted by one of the finest courts in the land and comprises two different types of jousting; a foot combat; and a masquerade ball.<ref name=moma121/> Freydal competes in each tournament and almost always wins.<ref name=Clephan87/> Once all the tournaments are completed, Freydal receives a letter from one of the noble ladies who, it transpires, is a powerful queen; in the letter, she professes her love for him. The narrative ends with Freydal setting out to search for her, and ''Theuerdank'' then takes up the subsequent story.<ref name=moma121/>\n\nThe work reflects Maximilian's vanity, as exemplified by a poem which forms part of the draft text:<ref name=\"Clephan 1995 88\"/>{{Quotation|This did the gallant Freydal<br>In knightly deeds of fame<br>Thus rendering illustrious<br>The glories of his name.<br>His virtues and his goodness<br>Are manifest to all;<br>His many glorious triumphs<br>At tilt, at masks and ball...<br>His like will ne\u2019er be seen again.<ref>translation {{harvnb|Clephan|1995|p=88, note 1}}</ref>}}\n\nHowever, the tournaments described are based on encounters Maximilian actually had. This is evidenced by a list of people involved in the story in the first seven [[Paper quire|quire]]s of the draft text, and who are known to have been actual courtiers.<ref name=Silver64/>\n\n===Illuminated manuscript tournament book===\n[[File:Freydal 02.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|left|Freydal in a \u201cjoust of war with flying and exploding shields\u201d (''Geschifttartschen-Rennen'') with Sigmund von Welsperg (''Freydal'' ms. fol. 29, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum|KMW]])<ref>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|pp=175\u2013176}}</ref>]]\nThe miniatures in the tournament book manuscript illustrate the types of [[jousting]] popular at the time, both on horse and on foot.<ref name=McLaren/> Freydal features in each illustrated combat and his opponent is an historical figure with whom Maximilian actually jousted.<ref name=McLaren/> Each picture, in the lower margin, identifies the name of the opponent and the other courtiers depicted.<ref name=Locke123>{{harvnb|Locke|2015|p=123}}</ref> Other tournament books exist, but ''Freydal'' is the largest from the late Middle Ages<ref name=moma120/> and is considered the best executed; it is also the only one to show spectacular falls.<ref name=McLaren/>\n\nTwo types of joust, ''Rennen'' (or \u201cjousts of war\u201d where the lance has a sharpened tip<ref name= joust>{{harvnb|Jeep|2001|p=759}}; {{harvnb|Silver|2002|p=63}}</ref>) and ''Stechen'' (or \u201cjousts of peace\u201d where the lance has a blunted tip<ref name= joust/>) are depicted for each tournament.<ref name=Clephan87/><ref name=moma121/> Within these two broad groupings, eleven sub-types are shown.<ref name=moma121/> In the ''Welsches Gestecht'' (Italian joust of peace) a board separates the jousters so that they can ride more closely to each other and strike their opponent frontally with greater force. This results in a spectacular splintering of the lances. In the ''Scharfrennen'' (joust of war with flying shields) the shield is shown loosely fixed to the rider's breastplate, the aim being to dislodge it. In contrast, the objective of the ''Antzogenrennen'' is to unseat the opponent and his shield is fixed to his armour.<ref name=moma121/> The ''Feldrennen'' (or ''Kampfrennen'') jousts replicate skirmishes in war and the riders wear battlefield armour. The rarest type of joust depicted is the ''Kr\u00f6nlrennen'' where one rider wears the armour of a joust of peace but wields the lance of a joust of war and the other rider  has the opposite combination.<ref name=moma122/>\n\nOne of the most spectacular jousts depicted is the ''Bundrennen'' (joust of war with flying shields without [[bevors]])<ref name=moma121/> and its variation, ''Geschifttartschen-Rennen'' (joust of war with flying and exploding shields).<ref name=moma125>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|p=125}}</ref> In the ''Bundrennen'', the shield is held in place on the rider's breastplate with a complicated spring mechanism and when it is struck in the right place by the opponent it is ejected high into the air.<ref name=moma121/> The ''Geschifttartschen-Rennen'' increases the spectacle by attaching multiple triangular platelets to the shield which, when the shield is ejected, come loose and explode into the air like a firework display.<ref name=moma125/> Maximilian claimed to have invented this type of joust.<ref name=Freeman/> \n[[File:Freydal 05.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|right|Foot combat between Freydal and Claude de Vaudry (''Freydal'' ms. fol. 39, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum|KMW]])<ref name=moma120/>]]\nIn each of the tournaments, the participants are shown engaging in a foot combat. A variety of weapons are used, including [[Mace (bludgeon)|iron clubs]] (''Eisenkolben''), [[Flail (weapon)|flails]] (''Drischel''), swords (''Turnierschwert'')<ref name=krause179>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|p=179}}</ref> and daggers.<ref name=krause181>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|p=181}}</ref> The ''[[Melee (tournament)|m\u00eal\u00e9e]]'' is also shown in the manuscript.<ref name=Clephan87/>\n\nAfter each of the sixty-four tournaments is a scene depicting a [[moresca]] (a pantomime dance) or other post-tournament festivities with male courtiers, including the knights who had competed in the tournament, dressing up to dance in a variety of exotic costumes.<ref name=Locke121/> Known as \u2018mummeries\u2019, these were a regular feature of the evening entertainment after tournaments.<ref name=moma122/>\n\nThe male courtiers in the mummeries in the manuscript dress up, amongst other things, in costumes based on nationality or ethnicity, for example [[Ottoman Turks|Turkish]], [[Republic of Venice|Venetian]] or [[Burgundian Netherlands|Burgundian]] costume, or as animals such as [[apes]] and creatures with bird's heads.<ref name=Locke121/> In one masquerade illustrated, the male participants engage in [[cross-dressing]] and wear women's gowns.<ref name=moma122/>\n\nIn each scene, all the men are dressed in the same costume and normally wear a mask. Women, however, are always shown wearing their usual court attire.<ref name=Locke121/> In each of these post-tournament pictures, Freydal appears carrying a torch and wearing a mask.<ref name=Locke121/> The ''Freydal'' illustrations constitute the most extensive pictorial record of these late medieval court masquerades.<ref name=moma122/>\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = center\n | header = <br>Scenes from the Kunsthistorisches Museum ''Freydal'' illuminated manuscript\n | total_width = 725\n | image_style = border:none;\n | perrow = 3\n\n | image2 = Freydal KK5073.jpg\n | alt2 = Flying shields\n | caption2 = ''Scharfrennen''&nbsp;\u2013 joust of war with flying shields (fol.157)\n\n | image1 = Stechen gegen Graf Sigmund von Hardegk.jpg\n | alt1 = Stechen\n | caption1 = ''Stechen''&nbsp;\u2013 joust of peace, against Sigmund von Hardegk (fol.106)\n\n | image3 = Freydal fol14.jpg\n | alt3 = Italian\n | caption3 = ''Welsches Gestecht''&nbsp;\u2013 Italian joust of peace (fol.14)\n\n | image4 = Freydal fol156 Mummerei.jpg\n | alt4 = Mummery\n | caption4 = Mummery festivities (fol.156)\n\n | image6 = Masquerade, Freydal manuscript, folio 207.jpg\n | alt6 = Cross-dressing mummery \n | caption6 = Cross-dressing mummery (fol. 207)\n\n | image5 = Freydal fol083.jpg\n | alt5 = Flail\n | caption5 = Foot combat with flails against Wilhelm Auer von Herrenkirchen zu Neudorf (fol.83)<ref name=krause179/>\n\n}}\n==Significance==\nTournament books were a feature of late medieval and renaissance courtly culture and provide a graphic record of the jousting and it\u2019s rituals. Notable examples include [[Le Livre des tournois|''King Ren\u00e9's Tournament Book'']] and the tournament books of the [[Electors of Saxony]].<ref name=KrauseNGA>{{harvnb|Krause|2014-15}}</ref> However, the ''Freydal'' illuminated manuscript is considered the most important<ref name=KrauseNGA/> and precious<ref name=Clephan87/> of this genre.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin|60em}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://etheses.whiterose.ac.uk/18205/ |title= The Tournament and its Role in the Court Culture of Emperor Maximilian I (1459-1519) |first=Natalie|last=Anderson |date=2017 |publisher=University of Leeds White Rose eTheses|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Robert Coltman|last= Clephan|title=The Mediaeval Tournament|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=aLzW7-TaSmYC&printsec=frontcover&dq=inauthor:%22Robert+Coltman+Clephan%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjCiaPqpermAhWpSRUIHee3DRsQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=1995|orig-year=1919|publisher=Courier Corporation|isbn=978-0-486-28620-4|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite news |first=Laura|last=Freeman|title= The joy of jousting |url= https://www.spectator.co.uk/2019/05/the-joy-of-jousting/ |newspaper=The Spectator |date= 4 May 2019 |accessdate=9 January 2020|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=John M. |last=Jeep|title=Medieval Germany: An Encyclopedia|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=PzorDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=isbn:9781351665407&hl=en&sa=X