{"title_page": "Matatiele", "text_new": "{{sources|date=December 2007}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Matatiele\n| pushpin_map             = South Africa Eastern Cape#South Africa\n| coordinates             = {{coord|30|20|32|S|28|48|22|E|region:ZA|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[South Africa]]\n| subdivision_type1       = Province\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Eastern Cape]]\n| subdivision_type2       = District\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Alfred Nzo District Municipality|Alfred Nzo]]\n| subdivision_type3       = Municipality\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Matatiele Local Municipality|Matatiele]]\n| subdivision_type4       = Main Place\n| established_title       = Established\n| leader_title            = Councillor\n| area_footnotes          = <ref name=\"census2011\">{{cite web |url=http://census2011.adrianfrith.com/place/295171 |title = Main Place Matatiele |work=Census 2011}} </ref>\n| area_total_km2          = 11.20\n| population_footnotes    = <ref name=\"census2011\" />\n| population_total        = 12466\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n<!-- demographics (section 1) -->\n| demographics_type1      = Racial makeup (2011)\n| demographics1_footnotes = <ref name=\"census2011\" />\n| demographics1_title1    = [[Bantu peoples of South Africa|Black African]]\n| demographics1_info1     = 83.5%\n| demographics1_title2    = [[Coloureds|Coloured]]\n| demographics1_info2     = 9.5%\n| demographics1_title3    = [[Indian South African|Indian]]/[[Asian South African|Asian]]\n| demographics1_info3     = 2.6%\n| demographics1_title4    = [[White South African|White]]\n| demographics1_info4     = 4.1%\n| demographics1_title5    = Other\n| demographics1_info5     = 0.4%\n<!-- demographics (section 2) -->\n| demographics_type2      = [[First language]]s (2011)\n| demographics2_footnotes = <ref name=\"census2011\" />\n| demographics2_title1    = [[Xhosa language|Xhosa]]\n| demographics2_info1     = 48.3%\n| demographics2_title2    = [[Sotho language|Sotho]]\n| demographics2_info2     = 23.5%\n| demographics2_title3    = [[South African English|English]]\n| demographics2_info3     = 14.3%\n| demographics2_title4    = [[Afrikaans]]\n| demographics2_info4     = 7.5%\n| demographics2_title5    = Other\n| demographics2_info5     = 6.4%\n<!-- blank fields (section 2) -->\n<!-- Other information -->\n| timezone1               = [[South African Standard Time|SAST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +2\n| postal_code_type        = [[List of postal codes in South Africa|Postal code]] (street)\n| postal_code             = 4730\n| postal2_code_type       = [[Post-office box|PO box]]\n| postal2_code            = 4730\n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbers in South Africa|Area code]]\n| area_code               = 039\n}}\n'''Matatiele''' is a mid-sized town serving the farming and trading communities of [[East Griqualand]] in the foothills of the western [[Drakensberg]], [[Eastern Cape]], [[South Africa]], on the border with [[KwaZulu-Natal]] and 20&nbsp;km from the southern frontier of [[Lesotho]]. [[Dairy]] farming is the principal activity. Good trout fishing is to be had in the numerous streams of the area. As a town, Matatiele is the reference point for all of the northern Transkei. \n\nThe name \"Matatiele\" is clearly a [[Sesotho language|Sotho]] word{{According to whom|date=October 2019}},  based on the Sesotho phrase \"matata aile\" meaning \"the ducks have gone\". In [[Phuthi language|Phuthi]], the town name is pronounced \"Madadiyela\". The common informal name for the town in any of the languages mentioned, including English, is \"Matat\". Those who are born there call it \"sweet Matat\". The town became more popular when a [[Generations (South African TV series)|Generations]] producer Mfundi Vundla wrote a story about Matatiele Where the Actor real name \"Nambitha Mpulawana\" acted as a Matatiele Born. there was also a Tv show called \"Matatiele\" that aired two families Xhosa and Sesotho families who were not getting along at all but unfortunately they could not stop children from dating, that forced them to sit on the table to negotiate [[lobola]]. Matatiele is the hometown of the socialist Selby Buhle Baqwa of Mzongwana.\n\nThe residents in and around Matatiele, as in most of the northern Transkei region, are generally bilingual in Hlubi, isiXhosa and Sesotho. Many speak English. Some also speak as a home language (or as a language of heritage) Phuthi, especially residents in Tsitsong and T\u0161episong. \n{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nEvidence of [[Stone Age]] inhabitants in the form of art adorning rocks are found throughout the area. In the early 1860s the [[Griqua people|Griquas]] settled here after migrating across the Drakensberg from [[Philippolis]]. The town was the centre of [[cattle]] rustling and gun-running and order was only restored in 1874 by the [[Cape Mounted Riflemen]]. The town became a municipality in 1904.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe town was part of Cape Province until being transferred to Natal in 1978. In 2005, the municipality was moved from the KwaZulu-Natal province to the Eastern Cape as part of the [[Twelfth Amendment of the Constitution of South Africa]], over the objections of the majority of residents, some of whom in response founded the [[African Independent Congress]].  On 18 August 2006 the [[Constitutional Court of South Africa|Constitutional Court]] ruled that the part of the 12th Amendment dealing with the transfer of  Matatiele from KwaZulu-Natal to the Eastern Cape was invalid due to insufficient consultation with stakeholders.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0,,2-7-12_1985286,00.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-07-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930201444/http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0,,2-7-12_1985286,00.html |archivedate=2007-09-30 }}</ref> The situation was eventually resolved, and Matatiele was confirmed as part of Eastern Cape province under the [[Thirteenth Amendment of the Constitution of South Africa|13th Amendment]].<ref>http://www.justice.gov.za/legislation/acts/const13th-2007gg.pdf</ref>\n\n==Notable people of Matatiele==\n* [[Mosiuoa Lekota]], politician leader of the [[Congress of the People (South African political party)|Congress of the People]]\n* [[Andile Jali]], footballer\n* [[Thulas Nxesi]], Minister of Public Works\n* [[Chris Jafta]], judge of the Constitutional Court of South Africa\n* [[Mthembeni Ndevu]], popularly known as [[Emtee (rapper)|Emtee]], hip hop musician and record producer\n* [[Innocent Mdledle]], footballer (Supersport United)\n* [[Siyabonga Siphika]], former footballer [[Bush Bucks F.C. (1957)|Bush Buscks F.C]]. & [[Maritzburg United F.C.]]\n* [[Innocent Mdledle]], left back footballer of [[Supersport United FC]]\n* [[Ntsikelelo Nyauza]], footballer [[Orlando Pirates FC]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Alfred Nzo District Municipality}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in the Matatiele Local Municipality]]\n", "text_old": "{{sources|date=December 2007}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Matatiele\n| pushpin_map             = South Africa Eastern Cape#South Africa\n| coordinates             = {{coord|30|20|32|S|28|48|22|E|region:ZA|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[South Africa]]\n| subdivision_type1       = Province\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Eastern Cape]]\n| subdivision_type2       = District\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Alfred Nzo District Municipality|Alfred Nzo]]\n| subdivision_type3       = Municipality\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Matatiele Local Municipality|Matatiele]]\n| subdivision_type4       = Main Place\n| established_title       = Established\n| leader_title            = Councillor\n| area_footnotes          = <ref name=\"census2011\">{{cite web |url=http://census2011.adrianfrith.com/place/295171 |title = Main Place Matatiele |work=Census 2011}} </ref>\n| area_total_km2          = 11.20\n| population_footnotes    = <ref name=\"census2011\" />\n| population_total        = 12466\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n<!-- demographics (section 1) -->\n| demographics_type1      = Racial makeup (2011)\n| demographics1_footnotes = <ref name=\"census2011\" />\n| demographics1_title1    = [[Bantu peoples of South Africa|Black African]]\n| demographics1_info1     = 83.5%\n| demographics1_title2    = [[Coloureds|Coloured]]\n| demographics1_info2     = 9.5%\n| demographics1_title3    = [[Indian South African|Indian]]/[[Asian South African|Asian]]\n| demographics1_info3     = 2.6%\n| demographics1_title4    = [[White South African|White]]\n| demographics1_info4     = 4.1%\n| demographics1_title5    = Other\n| demographics1_info5     = 0.4%\n<!-- demographics (section 2) -->\n| demographics_type2      = [[First language]]s (2011)\n| demographics2_footnotes = <ref name=\"census2011\" />\n| demographics2_title1    = [[Xhosa language|Xhosa]]\n| demographics2_info1     = 48.3%\n| demographics2_title2    = [[Sotho language|Sotho]]\n| demographics2_info2     = 23.5%\n| demographics2_title3    = [[South African English|English]]\n| demographics2_info3     = 14.3%\n| demographics2_title4    = [[Afrikaans]]\n| demographics2_info4     = 7.5%\n| demographics2_title5    = Other\n| demographics2_info5     = 6.4%\n<!-- blank fields (section 2) -->\n<!-- Other information -->\n| timezone1               = [[South African Standard Time|SAST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +2\n| postal_code_type        = [[List of postal codes in South Africa|Postal code]] (street)\n| postal_code             = 4730\n| postal2_code_type       = [[Post-office box|PO box]]\n| postal2_code            = 4730\n| area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbers in South Africa|Area code]]\n| area_code               = 039\n}}\n'''Matatiele''' is a mid-sized town serving the farming and trading communities of [[East Griqualand]] in the foothills of the western [[Drakensberg]], [[Eastern Cape]], [[South Africa]], on the border with [[KwaZulu-Natal]] and 20&nbsp;km from the southern frontier of [[Lesotho]]. [[Dairy]] farming is the principal activity. Good trout fishing is to be had in the numerous streams of the area. As a town, Matatiele is the reference point for all of the northern Transkei. \n\nThe name \"Matatiele\" is clearly a [[Sesotho language|Sotho]] word{{According to whom|date=October 2019}},  based on the Sesotho phrase \"matata aile\" meaning \"the ducks have gone\". In [[Phuthi language|Phuthi]], the town name is pronounced \"Madadiyela\". The common informal name for the town in any of the languages mentioned, including English, is \"Matat\". Those who are born there call it \"sweet Matat\". The town became more popular when a [[Generations (South African TV series)|Generations]] producer Mfundi Vundla wrote a story about Matatiele Where the Actor real name \"Nambitha Mpulawana\" acted as a Matatiele Born. there was also a Tv show called \"Matatiele\" that aired two families Xhosa and Sesotho families who were not getting along at all but unfortunately they could not stop children from dating, that forced them to sit on the table to negotiate [[lobola]].\n\nThe residents in and around Matatiele, as in most of the northern Transkei region, are generally bilingual in Hlubi, isiXhosa and Sesotho. Many speak English. Some also speak as a home language (or as a language of heritage) Phuthi, especially residents in Tsitsong and T\u0161episong. \n{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nEvidence of [[Stone Age]] inhabitants in the form of art adorning rocks are found throughout the area. In the early 1860s the [[Griqua people|Griquas]] settled here after migrating across the Drakensberg from [[Philippolis]]. The town was the centre of [[cattle]] rustling and gun-running and order was only restored in 1874 by the [[Cape Mounted Riflemen]]. The town became a municipality in 1904.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe town was part of Cape Province until being transferred to Natal in 1978. In 2005, the municipality was moved from the KwaZulu-Natal province to the Eastern Cape as part of the [[Twelfth Amendment of the Constitution of South Africa]], over the objections of the majority of residents, some of whom in response founded the [[African Independent Congress]].  On 18 August 2006 the [[Constitutional Court of South Africa|Constitutional Court]] ruled that the part of the 12th Amendment dealing with the transfer of  Matatiele from KwaZulu-Natal to the Eastern Cape was invalid due to insufficient consultation with stakeholders.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0,,2-7-12_1985286,00.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-07-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930201444/http://www.news24.com/News24/South_Africa/Politics/0,,2-7-12_1985286,00.html |archivedate=2007-09-30 }}</ref> The situation was eventually resolved, and Matatiele was confirmed as part of Eastern Cape province under the [[Thirteenth Amendment of the Constitution of South Africa|13th Amendment]].<ref>http://www.justice.gov.za/legislation/acts/const13th-2007gg.pdf</ref>\n\n==Notable people of Matatiele==\n* [[Mosiuoa Lekota]], politician leader of the [[Congress of the People (South African political party)|Congress of the People]]\n* [[Andile Jali]], footballer\n* [[Thulas Nxesi]], Minister of Public Works\n* [[Chris Jafta]], judge of the Constitutional Court of South Africa\n* [[Mthembeni Ndevu]], popularly known as [[Emtee (rapper)|Emtee]], hip hop musician and record producer\n* [[Innocent Mdledle]], footballer (Supersport United)\n* [[Siyabonga Siphika]], former footballer [[Bush Bucks F.C. (1957)|Bush Buscks F.C]]. & [[Maritzburg United F.C.]]\n* [[Innocent Mdledle]], left back footballer of [[Supersport United FC]]\n* [[Ntsikelelo Nyauza]], footballer [[Orlando Pirates FC]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Alfred Nzo District Municipality}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in the Matatiele Local Municipality]]\n", "name_user": "John H Taupin", "label": "safe", "comment": "Edited a typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matatiele"}
